# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1926-st-louis-cardinals-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] Louis Cardinals season** was the team's 45th season in St.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] Louis, Missouri and their 35th in the National League.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] The Cardinals went 89–65 during the season and finished first in the National League, winning their first National League pennant.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] In the World Series, they defeated the New York Yankees in 7 games, ending it by throwing out Babe Ruth at second base in the ninth inning of Game 7 to preserve a 3–2 victory.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] This was Rogers Hornsby's only full season as manager for the team.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] Catcher Bob O'Farrell won the MVP Award this year, batting .293, with 7 home runs and 68 RBIs.
[src:1926-st-louis-cardinals-season/1926-st-louis-cardinals-season] Led by RBI champion Jim Bottomley, the offense scored the most runs in the NL.
